******* How to use console during installation (recommended for you) ***********

Short answer: Yes—but only if you enable serial console for the installer.
By default, your current setup (VNC + CDROM) uses a graphical console, not virsh console.

🧠 What happens in your current setup

You used:

--graphics vnc
--cdrom alpine-virt-3.22.4-x86_64.iso

👉 So during install:

Console = VNC only
virsh console = ❌ won’t show installer
✅ How to use console during installation (recommended for you)

You need to install via serial console instead of VNC

✔ Option 1: Use serial console (best for GCP + CLI)

Create VM like this:

virt-install \
--name alpine1 \
--ram 1024 \
--vcpus 2 \
--disk path=/var/lib/libvirt/images/alpine1.qcow2,size=10 \
--os-variant alpinelinux3.22 \
--network network=default \
--graphics none \
--console pty,target_type=serial \
--cdrom /var/lib/libvirt/images/alpine-virt-3.22.4-x86_64.iso
🔌 Then connect:
virsh console alpine1

👉 You will see:

Boot logs
Login prompt
Can run setup-alpine
⚠️ Important detail

Alpine ISO may not automatically use serial console

If screen is blank after connect:

Press:
Enter

Or add kernel parameter (advanced):

console=ttyS0
✅ Option 2: Hybrid (VNC + console fallback)

You can keep both:

--graphics vnc \
--console pty,target_type=serial
👍 Best approach for you (on GCP)

Since:

VNC requires firewall + port
You are working mostly CLI

👉 Use:

--graphics none + virsh console
🧠 Simple rule
Method	Installation Console
VNC	GUI installer
Serial (virsh console)	CLI installer
Both enabled	Either works
🚀 Pro tip

For Alpine specifically:

Installer is CLI anyway (setup-alpine)
So serial console is perfect

